photo.description: The shell-shaped Piazza del Campo, the town square, which houses the Palazzo Pubblico and the Torre del Mangia, is an architectural treasure, and is famous for hosting the Palio. The Palazzo Pubblico, itself a great work of architecture, houses yet another important art museum. Included within the museum is Ambrogio Lorenzetti's series of frescos on the good government and the results of good and bad government, there are also some of the finest frescoes of Simone Martini and Pietro Lorenzetti.

photo.description: The Piazza Del Campo is filled with people waiting for the race to start. We didn't have the greatest view, but we were at least in a relatively high spot. We got there around quarter to 4 in the afternoon, the ceremonies (flags, drummers, ceremonial horse races, etc.) started around a quarter after 5, and the real race started around quarter to 8. It's a quick race, just a minute and a half, and by 8:15 we were back at the Duomo waiting for our friend Ilise and her parents. It was so totally worth hanging out there for four hours; I hope we can do it again some day!
